Dependabot commands and options
You can trigger Dependabot actions by commenting on this PR: - `@dependabot rebase` will rebase this PR - `@dependabot recreate` will recreate this PR, overwriting any edits that have been made to it - `@dependabot merge` will merge this PR after your CI passes on it - `@dependabot squash and merge` will squash and merge this PR after your CI passes on it - `@dependabot cancel merge` will cancel a previously requested merge and block automerging - `@dependabot reopen` will reopen this PR if it is closed - `@dependabot close` will close this PR and stop Dependabot recreating it. You can achieve the same result by closing it manually - `@dependabot show ignore conditions` will show all of the ignore conditions of the specified dependency - `@dependabot ignore this major version` will close this PR and stop Dependabot creating any more for this major version (unless you reopen the PR or upgrade to it yourself) - `@dependabot ignore this minor version` will close this PR and stop Dependabot creating any more for this minor version (unless you reopen the PR or upgrade to it yourself) - `@dependabot ignore this dependency` will close this PR and stop Dependabot creating any more for this dependency (unless you reopen the PR or upgrade to it yourself)
> **Note** > Automatic rebases have been disabled on this pull request as it has been open for over 30 days.

# Problem
I encountered a problem in the home_view.dart file, which resulted in a RenderFlex overflow issue. The issue occurred when the UI exceeded its available space, causing the layout to break.

![Image](https://drive.google.com/uc?id=1-5WRhx7JZRMnhxrHq_gkOpSJzHJqgXBX)
# Solution
To address the RenderFlex overflow issue, I made the following changes in the home_view.dart file:

1.Replaced the Container widget with the Card widget: The Card widget provides built-in padding and styling options, which helped to control the content within a defined boundary.

2.Added padding: By adding appropriate padding around the content, I ensured that the UI elements were properly spaced and didn't exceed the available space.

After implementing these changes, the RenderFlex overflow issue was resolved. The UI layout now behaves correctly, with no overflowing content.

![Image](https://drive.google.com/uc?id=1AgtnVcEBy0qGxbCrcwRqwqtbyvTbbE-c)

pr_body:
### Description
In this PR, I have implemented the **timer** feature. So now the user can set up a timer from 00:00:01 to 23:59:59. 

For navigating to the `TimerView`, I've implemented a `BottomNavigationBar`. This `BottomNavigationBar` consists of two items `HomeView` and `TimerView`.

On `TimerView` the user can select the duration of the timer, and start the timer with the play `FloatingActionButton`. 

As the timer starts, the user will be able to pause/resume, and stop it.

After starting the timer, the user can move to any of the pages in the app, bring the app to the background, or even terminate it, and the timer will still work. 

The above-mentioned thing works in any case if the timer is running or paused, the remaining timer duration is consistently persisted in the local storage. 

When the timer rings, the `TimerRingView` is shown which consists of an SVG, _Time's up_ text, and a stop button. 
 
### Proposed Changes
- Added an SVG to be utilized on `TimerRingView`.
- Added `isTimer` property to `AlarmModel`.
- Updated the `getLatestAlarm` function in `IsarProvider`.
- Updated the `refreshUpcomingAlarms` and `scheduleNextAlarm` functions in `HomeController`.
- Added new methods for timer and bottom navigation bar in `SecureStorageProvider`.
- Updated the bindings of the modules.
- Updated the routes.
- Added the `bottomNavigationBar`, `timer`, and `timerRing` modules.
- Added `bottomNavigationBarTheme` in `ThemeData`.
- Added methods related to `DateTime` conversion in `Utils`.

## Fixes #114 

## Screenshots


https://github.com/CCExtractor/ultimate_alarm_clock/assets/92971894/aa803eb9-1472-41e2-a7d5-0d15b89228d0

- [ ] Documentation has been updated to reflect the changes

- [ ] All tests are passing

pr_body:
### Description
I've implemented the splash screen to enhance the user experience and mask the loading time of the application. I've created a new folder in the already existing `modules` named `splashScreen`. I've followed the previous architecture of the application. In the `splashScreen` folder, I've created three folders named `bindings`, `controllers`, and `views`. In these folders, I've implemented the respective things. The duration of the splash screen is 1 second. It shows the logo and name of the application. I've also written a test for the `splash_screen_view` in the `test` folder of the application. 

### Proposed Changes
- Instead of directly redirecting to the `home` screen, now it first loads the `splash-screen`, and then after a delay of 1 second, redirects to the `home` screen of the application. 
- Added `splash_screen_view_test.dart` file in the `test` folder of the application. 
- Removed `widget_test.dart` file from the `test` folder of the application. 

## Fixes #40

### Description
I have added the pre-commit hooks for improved code formatting. With this, on each commit the executed bash script will append missing required trailing commas, and format the files. 

These changes are done for improved code consistency and readability. 

To activate the pre-commit hooks, contributors may refer to the newly added `Activating Pre-Commit Hooks` section in the CONTRIBUTING.md file. 

### Proposed Changes
- Added `pre_commit.sh` in the `.github/hooks` directory.

SQLite databases offer the advantage of being easily accessible across various native languages, thereby facilitating a smooth exchange of data.
